=== P-Gqa-1 Coverage Probe ===

Candidates: 5
Queries: 10

## Branch A - Pure typed SQL-style pipe builder
Q1 simple lookup: Clean
  call: Match.node Person.as_ "p" |> where (Person.name p = param name) |> return node p
  why: Linear lookup is readable and pipe-friendly.
Q2 single-hop join with property filter: Awkward
  call: Match.node Person.as_ "a" |> out KNOWS (node Person "b") |> where (Person.age a > param min_age) |> return [a.name; b.name]
  why: Works, but edge/node alternation inside a pipe already needs nested handles.
Q3 optional match: Awkward
  call: match_ p |> optional (out WORKS_AT company) |> return [node p; opt company]
  why: Optional match can be bolted on but makes the pipeline stateful.
Q4 variable-length path: Escape hatch
  call: raw_pattern "path = (a:Person {id: $a})-[:KNOWS*1..6]->(b:Person {id: $b})"
  why: Variable-length named path breaks the linear node-first API.
Q5 multi-stage WITH: Awkward
  call: match_ posted |> with_ [p; count post as posts] |> where (posts > param min_posts) |> return [p.name; posts]
  why: WITH is pipe-shaped, but typed aliases need a second expression language.
Q6 aggregation: Clean
  call: match_ lives_in |> return [city.name; count person as residents] |> order_by desc residents |> limit param_limit
  why: Aggregation/order/limit are clause-like and pipe well.
Q7 list parameter: Clean
  call: match_ person |> where (Person.id p in_ param_ids) |> return [node p]
  why: List parameter filter is clause-like.
Q8 map parameter: Awkward
  call: match_ person |> where (Person.country p = param_map filter country && Person.active p = param_map filter active)
  why: Map projection needs special parameter-access combinators.
Q9 bulk ingest via UNWIND: Escape hatch
  call: raw "UNWIND $rows AS row MERGE ... SET ..."
  why: UNWIND/MERGE/SET is not naturally represented by the match-first builder.
Q10 typed function call: Awkward
  call: match_any_edge "a" "r" "b" |> where (type_ r = param rel_type) |> return [node a; alias (type_ r) "rt"; node b]
  why: Works only after adding unlabelled node/rel and function-call helpers.
  clean=3 awkward=5 escape=2 fails=0 status=Survives with risk

## Branch B - Hybrid pattern DSL plus pipeable clauses
Q1 simple lookup: Clean
  call: match_ Pattern.(node "p" Person ~props:[name := param name]) |> return [node "p"]
  why: Pattern DSL owns graph shape; clauses stay linear.
Q2 single-hop join with property filter: Clean
  call: match_ Pattern.(node "a" Person -- rel KNOWS --> node "b" Person) |> where (prop "a" age > param min_age) |> return [prop "a" name; prop "b" name]
  why: Single-hop pattern is compact.
Q3 optional match: Clean
  call: match_ p |> optional Pattern.(node "p" -- rel WORKS_AT --> node "c" Company) |> return [node "p"; nullable_node "c"]
  why: Optional match is a clause over the same pattern language.
Q4 variable-length path: Clean
  call: match_ Pattern.(path "path" (node "a" Person -- rel KNOWS ~hops:(1,6) --> node "b" Person)) |> return [path "path"]
  why: Variable-length named path fits once pattern DSL has path and hops.
Q5 multi-stage WITH: Clean
  call: match_ posted |> with_ [var "p"; count "post" as_ "posts"] |> where (var "posts" > param min_posts) |> return [prop "p" name; var "posts"]
  why: WITH chains are naturally pipeable.
Q6 aggregation: Clean
  call: match_ lives_in |> return [prop "c" name; count "p" as_ "residents"] |> order_by desc "residents" |> limit limit
  why: Clause builder handles aggregation.
Q7 list parameter: Clean
  call: match_ Pattern.(node "p" Person) |> where (prop "p" id |> in_ (param ids)) |> return [node "p"]
  why: List params are ordinary expressions.
Q8 map parameter: Awkward
  call: where (prop "p" country = param_field filter country && prop "p" active = param_field filter active)
  why: Map params are possible but introduce stringly field access unless schema-typed.
Q9 bulk ingest via UNWIND: Awkward
  call: unwind rows "row" |> merge Pattern.(node "p" Person ~props:[id := field "row" id]) |> set [prop "p" name := field "row" name; prop "p" age := field "row" age]
  why: Expressible, but this adds non-pattern write clauses.
Q10 typed function call: Clean
  call: match_ Pattern.(anon_node "a" -- rel_var "r" --> anon_node "b") |> where (type_ "r" = param rel_type) |> return [node "a"; type_ "r" as_ "rt"; node "b"]
  why: Unlabelled nodes and type(r) fit expression helpers.
  clean=8 awkward=2 escape=0 fails=0 status=Survives

## Branch C - Cypher literal PPX with parameter typing
Q1 simple lookup: Clean
  call: [%cypher {|MATCH (p:Person {name: $name}) RETURN p|}] ~params ~decode
  why: Cypher remains itself; call-site is compact if PPX validation exists.
Q2 single-hop join with property filter: Clean
  call: [%cypher {|MATCH (a:Person)-[:KNOWS]->(b:Person) WHERE a.age > $min_age RETURN a.name, b.name|}] ~params ~decode
  why: Cypher remains itself; call-site is compact if PPX validation exists.
Q3 optional match: Clean
  call: [%cypher {|MATCH (p:Person {id: $id}) OPTIONAL MATCH (p)-[:WORKS_AT]->(c:Company) RETURN p, c|}] ~params ~decode
  why: Cypher remains itself; call-site is compact if PPX validation exists.
Q4 variable-length path: Awkward
  call: [%cypher {|MATCH path = (a:Person {id: $a})-[:KNOWS*1..6]->(b:Person {id: $b}) RETURN path|}] ~params ~decode
  why: Literal is compact, but return/path or write-shape inference needs substantial PPX support.
Q5 multi-stage WITH: Clean
  call: [%cypher {|MATCH (p:Person)-[:POSTED]->(post:Post) WITH p, count(post) AS posts WHERE posts > $min_posts RETURN p.name, posts|}] ~params ~decode
  why: Cypher remains itself; call-site is compact if PPX validation exists.
Q6 aggregation: Clean
  call: [%cypher {|MATCH (p:Person)-[:LIVES_IN]->(c:City) RETURN c.name, count(p) AS residents ORDER BY residents DESC LIMIT $limit|}] ~params ~decode
  why: Cypher remains itself; call-site is compact if PPX validation exists.
Q7 list parameter: Clean
  call: [%cypher {|MATCH (p:Person) WHERE p.id IN $ids RETURN p|}] ~params ~decode
  why: Cypher remains itself; call-site is compact if PPX validation exists.
Q8 map parameter: Clean
  call: [%cypher {|MATCH (p:Person) WHERE p.country = $filter.country AND p.active = $filter.active RETURN p|}] ~params ~decode
  why: Cypher remains itself; call-site is compact if PPX validation exists.
Q9 bulk ingest via UNWIND: Awkward
  call: [%cypher {|UNWIND $rows AS row MERGE (p:Person {id: row.id}) SET p.name = row.name, p.age = row.age|}] ~params ~decode
  why: Literal is compact, but return/path or write-shape inference needs substantial PPX support.
Q10 typed function call: Clean
  call: [%cypher {|MATCH (a)-[r]->(b) WHERE type(r) = $rel_type RETURN a, type(r) AS rt, b|}] ~params ~decode
  why: Cypher remains itself; call-site is compact if PPX validation exists.
  clean=8 awkward=2 escape=0 fails=0 status=Survives

